title: Grateful Dead Live at Knickerbocker Arena on 1990-03-24
lineage: Dat (Sony R500)> Behringer UltraMatch SRC2000> SEK'D Prodif Plus> Samplitude v7.02 Professional> SHN
description: Let The Good Times Roll, Help On The Way-> Slipknot!-> Franklin's Tower, Walkin' Blues, Loser, Desolation Row, Tennessee Jed, One More Saturday Night Playin' In The Band-> Uncle John's Band-> Terrapin Station-> Mind Left Body Jam-> Drums-> Space-> The Wheel-> All Along The Watchtower-> Stella Blue-> Not Fade Away, E: We Bid You Good Night

reviews.review_text: Choice AUD This be the goods............
3-24-90 Microphones too close to audience for me, but otherwise very clear.  And of course it was a classic 3 night stand of solid performances, in what was then a brand new arena.
nice show! Maybe a 4 maybe a 5..... I don't know!m It must be 5 for 90.  They are very inspired to rock this show, good AUD also.

More sound The other source with the most votes sounds like it's far back from the stage, there is lots of separation but this one is a few bars higher in terms of fidelity.

Yes.... The loser

very distant show with little echo witch is weird 


but dig how you hear the full range of the crowd from front to back... sounds like your sitting on the lawn far back....


LET THE GOOD TIMES ROLL
I can't believe this is an audience tape. A better one you'd be hard pressed to find. Much nicer sounding than the soundboard, in my opinion, and an absolutely sterling show.

Without Love Day to Day.... Ahh, such fond memories of this first night at The Knickerbocker, (Or what ever it called now..."The Hot Pockets Arena" - or whatever  ;-)

Security was *totally* unprepared for the night, and that was a relatively good thing. It might as well have been "general admission" as folks were pretty much crammed on the floor or sitting where ever they wanted to...

It was odd - the lights were still on when the band took the stage, and LTGTR was like a sound check in public.

THEN came what we'd been waiting for all of that wonderful Spring '90 show. H/S/F !  If memory serves, the lights were STILL on during this time, and people were finding their seats.  Yes, the Slipknot is too short, but what there is of it is some of the most intricate playing I ever saw the "Late era Dead" perform. There's an great YouTube video of this that's easy to find, and it focuses mostly on Phil. You can see what a difficult song Slipknot was to play when done right.

Add to that the best "Loser" EVER, and a great 2nd set, and I feel honored just to have been there. (Although, by the time Stella came around the smoke was SO thick it was hard to breathe.. ( don't think they had any sort of A/C running)

All in all, a magic show in the middle of a magic tour.

Good times.

(AND, BTW... This recording is indeed, "the goods" Get it while you can !  It's the stuff of great trips...)

Listen to this Loser now and never stop listening to it ever! It's the best one ever IMHO though I always love a good debate. Just simply amazing. Soulful, understated, stately and just masterfully executed. The Organ riffs from Brent lock the groove in really nice and Jerry lays his whole heart out there in front of everyone during that solo. It scorches.

The rest of the show is pretty great too! Nice representation of the spring 1990 phenomenon.
